The relationship between ecosystem service provision and landuse is both
 important and imprecisely understood.
 Despite many calls to preserve land from development because of ecosystem
 service value, ecologists are rarely able to provide precise and specific
 estimates of the service provided by individual parcels.
 As a result, regulators seeking to implement payment for ecoystem service
 approaches are left uncertain about what they might be purchasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, I develop a stylized model to capture one essential tradeoff
 facing regulators in developing such policies: wait to gain improved scientific
 understanding of the relationship between land use change and ecosystem
 service provision or intervene today to prevent irreversible land development.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To focus on the timing question, the model simplifies many important realities.
 Most importantly, the model does not consider relationships between the
 total amount of land conserved and the ecosystem services provided by a
 specific parcel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two period schematic -- long time frames not annual probabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individual parcels have three characteristics: an ecosystem service value
 that describes the true value the parcel provides to society each period
 that it remains conserved, a public development value that describes the
 true value the parcel provides to society if it is developed, and a private
 development value that describes the individual landowner's private per
 period net benefit from developed land.
 If there were no externalities, the private development value would be
 the difference between the public development value and the ecosystem service
 value and landowners' development decisions would be optimal.
 Due to potential externalities related to both development and conservation,
 this relationship does not hold; the modeling structure in the paper allows
 for a variety of possible externalities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Development is irreversible in this model so the model considers only parcels
 that are undeveloped at the beginning of the time period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Timing and information structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 0, all parties know the public development of each parcel of land.
 The private development value of an individual parcel is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Landowners know the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv_{i}$
\end_inset

 for their own land, but regulators know its distribution.
 In addition to development value, parcels of land provide ecosystem service
 value when they are undeveloped.
 The net public benefit of conservation for a parcel is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The socially optimal use of land would thus be to develop any parcel with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 and to conserve any parcel with 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The challenge is that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}$
\end_inset

 is unknown.
 Moreover, since land use is decided privately, the regulator must induce
 individual landowners to make the appropriate land use choice, but the
 regulator does not know exactly how much individual landowners value conservati
on versus development.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key tradeoff in the model is between waiting for better information
 and conserving land today.
 At time 0, the regulator knows only distribution of possible values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 At time 1, the regulator observes a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\se_{i}$
\end_inset

 that reveals information about the true environmental service value.
 For analytical tractability, I assume that the variable have a multivariate
 normal distribution with the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\se_{i}\\
\priv_{i}\\
\env_{i}
\end{array}\right]\sim N_{4}\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\mu_{\priv}\\
\mu_{\env}
\end{array}\right],\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rhoES\rhoEP\sigma_{\priv} & \rho_{\env\se}\sigma_{\env}\\
\rhoES\rhoEP\sigma_{\priv} & \sigma_{\priv}^{2} & \rho_{\env\priv}\sigma_{\env}\sigma_{\priv}\\
\rho_{\env\se}\sigma_{\env} & \rho_{\env\priv}\sigma_{\env}\sigma_{\priv} & \sigma_{\env}^{2}
\end{array}\right]\right).
\]

\end_inset

With this structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\env\se}\in\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 measures the quality of the signal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\env\priv}$
\end_inset

 measures the correlation between environmental serice value and private
 development value, and the signal only provides information about private
 development value through the information it reveals about environmental
 service value.
